	<article>

		<header>
			
			<h1>Europeans want sustainably sourced fish, shows a WWF poll</h1>

			
			<h4>
												12 May 2011
										</h4>

					</header>


		
		
					<p>WWF has announced the results of an independent poll that found that an overwhelming majority of European consumers want the seafood they buy to come from sustainable sources. The poll results suggest that reform of the EU’s Common Fisheries Policy (CFP) is ‘urgently needed,’ as 78% of respondents favour a CFP reform that ensures that all European-caught seafood products come from sustainable fisheries.</p><p>Carried out in 14 EU countries, the poll found that 88% of respondents believe it is important that seafood products come from sustainable fisheries. The results of the poll are especially impressive in southern European countries (Portugal 92%, France 93%, Spain 91%, Italy 95%) and in Belgium (91%) where over 90% of respondents think it is important that fish on sale comes from non-overfished sustainable stocks. ‘It is interesting to see that in countries where fishing is an important sector, like Portugal, France or Spain, people are even more convinced that the sustainability of fish needs to be given absolute priority in a policy reform. With the European Parliament’s new co-decision powers on fisheries policy, we now have the opportunity and the responsibility to set things right for a really new CFP,’ said a Portuguese MEP.</p><p>The survey also found that 72% of consumers do not feel they have adequate information on the origin of the seafood they buy. A total of 72% of Europeans also feel that they lack adequate information about whether the fish on sale comes from well-managed, sustainable sources.</p><p>Commenting on this, the head of sustainable development at the Carrefour group said: ‘The poll results clearly show that consumers are keen to know that their consumption of fish is not contributing to overfishing. They need to have better information about the sustainability of the products they buy. This requires policy changes, but also action from the retail sector.’</p>
		
		
				<div class="box related">
			<h3>Sources</h3>
			
<p>
WWF, ‘A big appetite for sustainable fish’, press release and poll results, 12 April 2011<br/>
http://wwf.panda.org/?uNewsID=199996<br/>
Press article, <i>ATUNA</i>, ‘Carrefour: sustainability information on fish requires action retail business’, 15 April 2011<br/>http://www.atuna.com/news.html</p>		</div>
		
		
				<div class="box">
			<h3>Editorial comment</h3>
			<p>The reform of the EU CMO will provide an opportunity to review the labelling requirements for fish products, and to amend these in ways that provide more adequate information to consumers. This reform may also put in place an EU system to ensure that the claims made by eco-labels, that fish come from environmentally sustainable sources, are correct. However, this poll raises various questions. Other studies tend to show that, although European consumers are indeed keen on consuming fish from sustainable sources, they are not always ready to pay a premium price for it. This is especially the case for products that are considered to be a cheap source of fish protein, such as canned tuna. Obtaining a premium price for fish caught sustainably, a key issue for exporting countries (such as many in the ACP) that want to capture any benefits from value addition, may be easier in the non-retail sector (restaurants, catering, etc). This could be a market well worth exploring.</p>
		</div>
		
